{
  "doc_id": "47204",
  "text": "Some interventions that have been designed to increase learner self-efficacy have produced increases in training performance [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] indicating selfefficacy is a malleable learner characteristic (in contrast to trainees' innate intelligence). For example, support for including self-efficacy development methods to enhance transfer have been demonstrated: (a) when mastery experiences and supportive feedback were included as a transfer intervention [CITATION_5] , (b) when goal setting and self-management strategies were used in a posttraining transfer intervention [CITATION_6] , and (c) when participants used verbal self-guidance as part of a transfer intervention [CITATION_7] .",
